entry.title: [GWP-ASan] Switch to a faster PRNG
entry.content:
Currently, GWP-ASan utilizes a random number generator that fetches

entropy from the operating system for each call. This approach is

computationally intensive and exceeds the needs of GWP-ASan's specific

use case.



This CL introduces a more efficient XorShift PRNG, which maintains its

state in a thread-local variable, leveraging the existing thread-local

storage code from the `SamplingState` class.



Local tests show a 2x speed improvement in

`RecordLightweightDeallocation`, and a 1.22x speedup in a pair of

`GPA::Allocate` and `GPA::Deallocate` calls.

entry.title: Refactor @OnlyRunFor* into @IgnoreFor(implementations={...})
entry.content:
Soon we will also have CronetPlatformProvider, meaning that there

will be more than two implementation accessible within Chromium.



Due to that, it will be possible to run tests against multiple

implementations, while not running them against all (i.e., filter

a single implementation out). The current @OnlyRunFor* test annotation

are not too well suited for that.



To fix the above, introduce the context of CronetImplementation and

refactor @OnlyRunFor* to make use of that.

entry.title: Prerender: Support PreloadingAttempt for prerender-into-new-tab
entry.content:
- PreloadingAttempt is associated with WebContents.

Prerender-into-new-tab creates its own WebContents (known as prerender

WebContents) and their PreloadingAttempt is associated with that.



- When a prerendered page is not activated (e.g., a primary page that

triggered prerendering navigates to a different page), Chrome records

PreloadingAttempt UKM with the primary page (to be more precise,

Preloading_Attempt_PreviousPrimaryPage), not the prerendered page, as

UKM cannot be recorded with pages that are never visible to users.

This is a bit tricky for prerender-into-new-tab because in their case

the primary trigger page and the prerendered page are in separate

WebContents. To support this, when prerender-into-new-tab starts, it

passes a UKM source ID of the primary page

(triggering_primary_page_source_id) to PreloadingAttempt and then let

it record the UKM with the ID in the case where activation doesn't

happen.



- This CL extends test helpers to handle the case explained above.



This CL supports only PreloadingAttempt. Other precog UKMs like

PreloadingPrediction will be supported by follow-up CLs.

entry.title: Correct PrintingContextWin error handling for enumerating printers
entry.content:
If the Windows print spooler is disabled then the GDI call to

EnumPrinters() fails. In this case the return value shows failure and

the error code shows the server is not available. The GDI call also

modifies the provided out parameters: the count of printers is set to

zero and the bytes needed is set to some random value, which looks like

it is an uninitialized value.



Since the error handling in PrintingContextWin::UseDefaultSettings()

was only relying upon the bytes needed value, this can result in

out-of-memory errors by trying to use the uninitialized value to

allocate the printer info buffer.



Modify the basic error checking around the EnumPrinters() call to mimic

what is done in PrintBackendWin::EnumeratePrinters(), which correctly

addresses this situation. Do not have PrintingContextWin directly use

PrintBackendWin, as that would incur extra overhead, given that

PrintingContextWin is only interested in the first possible printer and

not all of them.

entry.title: Allow for 16 GiB PDBs and debug component builds
entry.content:
Originally Chrome's PDBs could be a maximum of 4 GiB. That limit became

constraining and support for larger PDBs became available so the limit

was raised to 8 GiB. That is good enough for "normal" use, but when

doing debug non-component builds the PDB for chrome.dll gets very close

to 8 GiB, and browser_tests.exe.pdb is about 9.6 GiB.



Changing from an 8 KiB page size to 16 KiB page size lets us support

PDBs up to 16 GiB which should be enough for the foreeseable future. The

only known cost is that PDBs get about 2.3% larger. By only using the

16 KiB page size for debug non-component builds we can avoid paying

this cost when we don't need to.



With 16 GiB PDBs the formerly unsupported debug non-component build

flavor becomes supportable. Link times are still slow (almost two

minutes on my chrome.dll.pdb tests) but the debugging experience can be

superior in some cases.



Prior to this change the debug non-component build was accidentally

supported on Windows, but only if the NOP flag use_debug_fission=true

was set. Now this configuration is intentionally and properly supported.



A debug component build is desirable because some types are defined

in one component (DLL in Windows) and used in another component. In

this situation there is no type information for the type in the DLL

where the type is used, so the debugger can't show the object

internals. This makes for a bad debugging experience.



The debug component builds are slow to build and debug, so they won't

be catching on anytime soon, but for some problems they are

invaluable.

entry.title: Create a handle system for UI objects.
entry.content:
An object that |SupportsHandles| allows you to call GetHandle() to return a handle to that object. Handles are opaque objects that are serializable but from which the original object can be retrieved if it still exists.



The integral type for the opaque handle may be specified in order to ensure adequate bits for the rolling counter, and the behavior when the counter rolls over can also be specified. The fact that rollover is possible is the major disadvantage vs. |WeakPtr|, which is almost always the better choice if you do not need serializability.



This is a prerequisite for a lot of stability work we are doing in

the tabstrip model and related systems.

entry.title: [A11y] Don't detach an object while updating its cached values
entry.content:
When detaching an object from a parent, we sometimes destroy its

subtree as well, if the subtree only makes sense in the context of its

parent. This is true for image map areas, but our check for that was

not tight enough. As a result, an object inside of a role=image

could be destroyed by a chain of recursive cached value updates that

ends up calling SetNeedsToUpdateChildren() on the parent.

The fix for this is sufficient to fix the repro

case in the bug, but it may not fix all cases of the bug.



Therefore, in lieu of a test, a new check has been added to ensure

that an object will not be detached while in the middle of updating its

cached values, so if there are more instances of the issue, we will get

more useful stacks and information.



Fixed: 1480267

entry.title: Don't save snap fraction too early for ARC
entry.content:
With crrev.com/c/4713908, PiP snap fraction is saved for the first

time in OnWindowVisibilityChanged(). This is done here because

in most cases PiP gets visible after everything is set up for the

window, but it turns out in the case of an ARC window getting into

PiP from minimized, visibility is updated when window state change

happens, which is too early because at this point the bounds for

PiP hasn't been set yet.



For ARC PiP, snap fraction is saved in

ClientControlledShellSurface::OnPostWidgetCommit(), where an ARC

window is fully ready for PiP, so for ARC PiP, we should skip

setting snap fraction in OnWindowVisibilityChanged().
